:::summary
Latter-day Saint doctrine — the theology of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints — is a restored form of ancient Christianity revealed through the Prophet Joseph Smith beginning in 1820. It differs significantly from traditional Catholic and Protestant theology in its understanding of God, human nature, salvation, and the afterlife. Central to LDS doctrine is the belief that God the Father and Jesus Christ are distinct, embodied beings; that humanity's divine potential is eternal progression; and that the priesthood authority and saving ordinances of the original Church have been restored.
:::

